Jenkins: test this please.

I've captured the workspace for the Windows re-run, but one thing that strikes me from this [rerun's log](https://grpc-testing.appspot.com/job/gRPC_pr_win/6932/consoleFull) is this assert:

```
E0728 04:32:39.119000000  7324 call_combiner.c:101] assertion failed: prev_size >= 1
```

Right, reading the code and the previous runs, this really reeks of a threading issue where `grpc_call_combiner_start` and `grpc_call_combiner_stop` are being called from threads they shouldn't have been called from. We'll have to discuss about how to tackle that one. And I am guessing this didn't reproduce initially because it requires some I/O pressure on the machine to get to that state. But I might have a way to force that state under a debugger. I'll try it tomorrow.

It doesn't actually matter which threads call_combiner_start() and call_combiner_stop() are called from; the assert just means that we've called call_combiner_stop() more times than we've called call_combiner_start(), which should not be happening.

Unfortunately, in order to debug this, I need either (a) a stack trace of the failure or (b) a run with that assertion failure with GRPC_TRACE=call_combiner enabled.  Without either of those, I'm shooting blind, because I can't reproduce the problem on Linux.

Looks like the bm_diff suite are revealing a race-y bug. I took a look at the jenkins log; all the failures are due to this assertions failure:

`E0728 04:33:00.804786268   10551 call_combiner.c:101]        assertion failed: prev_size >= 1`

Also, this PR shows performance degradation. Not just in atomics, but in cpu and real time. 

I don't think that should block this change, but I do think that it would be worth linking to a doc that explains why we are willing to take a performance hit here.

Thanks, Noah -- it looks like that's the same problem we're tracking down on Windows.  Hopefully, once we fix that bug, both things will start working.

Craig took at look at the bm_diff output for this PR before he left and indicated that it didn't look like a significant performance problem to him.  I do see a few benchmarks where there's some additional CPU or wall time, but I'm guessing those can be optimized with a little more work, and it's neutral on the vast majority of the benchmarks.

Ultimately, I think this approach will be much more scalable.  We can talk more about it when I present at the team meeting next week.
